udy of Three Brazilian Films and their Intermedial Characters -- t13 Gilda de Abreu’s O Ébrio as a Unique Intermedial Project -- t14 Chanchada, Samba and Beyond: From the Cinema of Radio to the Cinema of Television (1930s–1960s) -- tPart IV From Impure Cinema to Cosmopoetics -- t15 Impure Cinema as Method: The Last Films of Eduardo Coutinho -- t16 Queering Intermediality in Brazilian Cinema -- t17 The Humiliation of the Father: Theatrical Melodrama and Cinema Novo’s Critique of Conservative Modernisation -- t18 Intermedial Territories: Maps and the Amazonian Moving Image -- t19 An Intermedial Reading of Glauber Rocha’s Cosmogony -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPresents a new history of Brazilian Cinema, based on its dialogue with other arts and mediaLaunches an entirely new historiographic method, drawing on intermediality in order to reconstruct the history of a national cinemaUnveils the multimedia and polymathic wealth behind the various historical periods in Brazilian cinemaProvides an overarching historical coverage of Brazilian cinema, through an innovative approach that connects different periods in Brazilian film history through the multiple art and media forms interwoven in themProposes that different phases of a national cinema can be framed as comparable and interrelated phenomena, rather than relying on evolutionary chronologies and classical-modern or centre-periphery modelsExplores new ways of understanding Brazilian film history, and the history of cinema in generalFrom its inception, Brazilian cinema has combined extra-filmic artistic and cultural forms, both local and imported, resulting in an original aesthetic blend. Theatre, dance, music, circus, radio, television and the plastic arts left a distinctive mark on Brazilian cinema’s poetics and politics, as can be observed in a host of fascinating phenomena analysed in this book, including: the film prologues that connected the screen to the stage in the 1920s; the chanchada musical comedies, inflected by vaudeville theatre and the radio; the manguebeat and árido movie movements that blurred the boundaries between music and film; and contemporary multimedia installations and other experiments. By adopting intermediality as a historiographic method, this book reconstructs the history and cultural wealth behind filmic expressions in Brazilian cinema.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aIntermediality. 0aMotion pictureszBrazilxHistory. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh1 aAdamatti, Margarida Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeugnet, Martine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCesarino Costa, Flávia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorrêa de Araújo, Luciana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElduque, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLins, Consuelo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLira de Sousa, Ramayana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuca, Tiago de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuna Freire, Rafael de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNagib, Lúcia , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNagib, Lúcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaiva, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat